'''Preston Bruce Austin''' (9 December 1827 &ndash; 7 July 1908) was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] clergyman, barrister and [[cricket]]er.

==Life==
He was the third of the family of ten, and second son, of the Rev. Wiltshire Stanton Austin, and brother of [[Francis Austin]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Kortright Davis|title=Cross and Crown in Barbados: Caribbean Political Religion in the Late 19th Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uOFMAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA76|date=1 May 2011|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|isbn=978-1-61097-061-7|page=76}}</ref><ref>{{acad|id=ASTN848PB|name=Austin, Preston Bruce}}</ref> Born at [[Llwydcoed]], [[Glamorgan]], Austin made one [[first-class cricket]] appearance for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]] while undertaking studies there. His only appearance came against the [[Gentlemen of Kent]] at the [[St Lawrence Ground]] in 1848,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/36/36252/First-Class_Matches.html|title=First-Class Matches played by Preston Austin|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> scoring 6 runs in the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/0/824.html|title=Gentlemen of Kent v Cambridge University, 1848|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> He later moved to the [[British West Indies]], while living there he stood as an [[umpire (cricket)|umpire]] in one first-class cricket match in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/36/36252/Umpire_in_First-Class_Matches.html|title=Preston Austin as Umpire in First-Class Matches|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref>

Having attended [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]], Austin was ordained as a [[deacon]] in 1851.<ref name="BIO">{{cite web|url=http://dspace.dial.pipex.com/town/walk/rcr51/ThomasAustin/tree/pafn06.htm|title=Descendents of Thomas Austin of Barbados|publisher=|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> After spending time in Germany, he moved to [[Demerara]] in [[British Guiana]], during which he was the assistant master of [[Queen's College, Guyana|Queen's College, Georgetown]], a college which played an important role in establishing cricket in British Guiana. He later moved to [[Barbados]], founding the St. John the Baptist Church in [[Saint James, Barbados|St. James Parish]] on the island, of which he was rector from 1860 until 1865.<ref name="BIO"/> Austin later opposed the plans of Barbados governor [[John Pope Hennessy]] for a federation of the [[Windward Islands]], which would result in Barbados' self-government. He travelled to London to present a petition of opposition to the [[Colonial Office]].<ref name="BIO"/> He was the rector of [[Saint Philip, Barbados|Saint Philip]] from 1875 to 1880, after which he returned to England having left the church 'under a cloud'.<ref name="BIO"/> He spent the following twenty years in England, where he was the rector of [[All Hallows Lombard Street]]. His wife died in 1900 and he returned to live with one of his sons back in Barbados, where he died in on 7 July 1908.<ref name="BIO"/> He was buried at St. John the Baptist Church, his grave marked as 'the Founder'.<ref name="BIO"/> In addition to being a clergyman, Austin was also a barrister.

==Family==
Austin married on 9 December 1854, in the [[Cathedral Church of Saint Michael and All Angels]], Barbados, Anna Eliza Griffith, daughter of Richard S. Griffith M.D. of Barbados.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001427/18550106/072/0008|title=Marriages|date=6 January 1855|work=Morning Advertiser|pages=8|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=David Dobson|title=American Vital Records from the Gentleman's Magazine, 1731-1868|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MNz0xpd8M1EC&pg=PA120|year=1987|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Com|isbn=978-0-8063-1177-7|page=120}}</ref>

